{{Refimprove|date=January 2009}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Sestos | native_name = Σηστός | alternate_name = | image = Thracian chersonese.png | alt = | caption = Sestos and the [[Hellespont]] | map_type = Turkey | map_alt = | map_size = 275 | relief = | coordinates = {{coord|40|13|N|26|23|E|display=inline,title}} | location = Bigalı, [[Çanakkale Province]], [[Turkey]] | region = [[Thracian Chersonese]] | type = Settlement | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }}
'''Sestos''' ({{lang-el|Σηστός}}) or '''Sestus''' was an [[ancient Greek]] town of the [[Thracian Chersonese]],<ref>[http://www2.le.ac.uk/departments/archaeology/people/shipley/pseudo-skylax Pseudo-Skylax, The 'Periplous' (Circumnavigation): a provisional translation, paragraphs 66, 67]</ref> the modern [[Gallipoli]] peninsula in European [[Turkey]]. Situated on the [[Hellespont]] opposite [[Abydos (Hellespont)|Abydos]], it was the home of Hero in the legend of [[Hero and Leander]], where according to legend she lived in a tower overlooking the sea. Sestos was an [[Aeolians|Aeolian]] colony, as it was founded by settlers from [[Lesbos]]. The ruins of the town are near to the modern settlement of [[Eceabat]].
During the [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian]] rule, Sestos alongside [[Byzantium]] were the two Achaemenid ports of utmost importance on the European coasts of the [[Bosphorus]] and the [[Hellespont]].{{sfn|Balcer|1990|pages=599-600}} In 480 BC, [[Xerxes I|Xerxes']] army crossed at this point on two temporary [[pontoon bridge]]s later known as [[Xerxes' Pontoon Bridges]], and most of [[Alexander the Great]]'s forces went the other way here by boat in 334 BC.
In 1810 [[Lord Byron]] swam from Sestos to Abydos in one hour 10 minutes, recreating Leander's feat, and wrote a poem thereafter.<ref>[[s:The Works of Lord Byron (ed. Coleridge, Prothero)/Poetry/Volume 3/Written after swimming from Sestos to Abydos]]</ref> This event is commemorated every year with an annual swim event that recreates the crossing.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2007/sep/30/escape.turkey</ref>
Little now remains of the ancient town of Sestos.
[[File:Sestusdecree-BM.JPG|250px|left|thumb| Marble decree from Sestos in the [[British Museum]]]]
==Hero and Leander==
Sestos is central to [[Christopher Marlowe]]'s poem ''[[Hero and Leander (poem)|Hero and Leander]]'', and is referred to in its opening lines: <poem> ''On Hellespont, guilty of true love's blood, ''In view and opposite two cities stood, ''Sea-borderers, disjoin'd by Neptune's might: ''The one Abydos, the other Sestos [[:wikt:hight|hight]]. ''At Sestos Hero dwelt; Hero the fair, ''Whom young Apollo courted for her hair. </poem> The poem's two parts are called "Sestiads".
==Siege of Sestos== {{Main|Greco-Persian Wars}}
In 479-478 BC, after the Greek victories (against Persia) at [[Battle of Plataea|Plataea]] and [[Battle of Mycale|Mycale]], Greek forces under the command of [[Xanthippus]] besieged the Persian forces. The Athenians attacked the Persian forces, and defeated the Persians. Since the Persians were defeated, the Persian garrison at Sestos allowed the Greeks to conquer the city. As a result, Persian influence along the [[Hellespont]] was significantly reduced. This served the dual goal of denying Persian land forces access to the Greek mainland, while restoring Athenian trade to [[Black Sea]] ports such as [[Byzantium]].
